{{italic title}} {{Infobox artwork | title = We, Too, Have a Job to Do | image_file = We, too, have a Job to Do.jpg | artist = [[Norman Rockwell]] | year = 1942 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_imperial = 30 | width_imperial = 22 | height_metric = 76 | width_metric = 56 | museum = [[National Scouting Museum]] }} '''''We, Too, Have a Job to Do''''' is a painting by American illustrator [[Norman Rockwell]] that depicts a [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scout]] in full uniform standing in front of a waving [[Flag of the United States|American flag]]. It was originally created by Rockwell in 1942 for the 1944 [[Brown & Bigelow]] Boy Scout Calendar.<ref>{{Cite web|title = We, Too, Have a Job To Do|url = https://history.lds.org/media/we-too-have-a-job-to-do-brown-and-bigelow?lang=eng#1|website = Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints History|accessdate = 2015-12-28}}</ref> The model, Bob Hamilton, won a contest to be in the painting and personally delivered a print to the [[Vice President of the United States]] at the time, [[Henry A. Wallace]].
== Creation == The painting was created to encourage Scouts to participate in the [[war effort]] during [[World War II]].<ref name=":0" /> The name of the painting, ''We, Too, Have a Job to Do'', comes from a slogan that the Boy Scouts of America used in 1942 to rally scouts to support the troops by collecting metal and planting [[victory garden]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|title = We Too Have A Job To Do!|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=aQteiT0ObU8C|publisher = Boy Scouts of America|date = 1942-03-01|first = James E|last = West|work = Boys' Life}}</ref>
The model, Bob Hamilton, won a contest with his local council in [[Albany, New York]], to be depicted in the painting.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url = |title = World War II icon dies at 82: Rockwell model inspired scouts to aid country, community|last = Monteleone|first = James|date = August 3, 2008|work = Farmington Daily Times|access-date = |via = LexisNexis}}</ref> He traveled to Rockwell's studio in [[Arlington, Vermont]], to model for Rockwell.<ref name=":1" /> Since Hamilton was a scout, the uniform shown in the painting was his, unlike some of Rockwell's other models. Originally, he wore a turtle shell [[Woggle|neckerchief slide]] with his uniform that he had made. Rockwell did not like it and asked Hamilton to swap it for a simpler [[Turk's head knot|Turk's head]] slide.<ref name=":2" /> In 1944, Hamilton personally delivered a copy of the painting to Vice President Henry A. Wallace.<ref name=":2" /> Hamilton later became an [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]], served in the [[US Navy|Navy]], and worked for the Boy Scouts.<ref name=":1" /> He died in July 2008, at the age of 82.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/news/state/aprockwell08-04-08.htm |title=Model for Rockwell Boy Scout Painting Dies at 82 |newspaper=[[Albuquerque Journal]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=August 4, 2008 |accessdate=May 13, 2017}}</ref>
== Composition == The painting depicts a Boy Scout giving the [[Scout sign and salute|Scout salute]]; behind him is an American flag, rippling in an unseen breeze.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url = |title = Brave, Trustworthy, Loyal, Obedient Norman Rockwell's Reverent Portraits of America's Youthful Ideal|last = Allen|first = Henry|date = April 26, 1996|work = Washington Post|access-date = |via = LexisNexis}}</ref> The Scout's face is solemn yet confident.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=20080805&id=EKs0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=62wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3393,4737539&hl=en|title = Arthur Robert "Bob" Hamilton|last = |first = |date = August 5, 2008|work = Kentucky New Era|access-date = |via = |agency = Associated Press}}</ref> His brown eyes, cleft chin, and idealized face stand out to the viewer.<ref name=":0" /> The Scout's uniform is perfect, with a [[campaign hat]], showing that he is a [[First Class Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|First Class Scout]]. A [[Cub Scout#Organization|Den Chief]] cord hangs over the Scout's right shoulder, and a backpack hangs over his left shoulder.
== Meaning == The painting represents the idea that there is always work to be done in a Scout's neighborhood and that it is a Scout's duty to do it.<ref name=":2" />
